<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Insurance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Life insurance is, financially, a bet =
on your early death. If you=C2=A0buy a 20-year term life insurance policy w=
ith a $5 million death benefit and premiums of $25,000 a=C2=A0year,<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and you live for 21 more years, then you pay a total of $500,000 =
in premiums and get back $0 in benefits. If you buy that same policy and di=
e the day after you buy it, you pay roughly $0 of premiums and get back $5 =
million of benefits. The earlier you die, the better you do. Financially.=
=C2=A0Only financially. Otherwise you=E2=80=99d prefer to die later.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the central problem is that, if the ins=
urance policy=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>pay out the $5 million,=C2=A0<em>you=
=C2=A0</em>don=E2=80=99t get it. You=E2=80=99re dead; that is the prerequis=
ite for getting the money. Somebody else gets it. Ordinarily that somebody =
else will be your heirs:=C2=A0your spouse, your children, whoever. You hope=
 that they too will prefer that you die later, even if it means that they d=
on=E2=80=99t get the $5 million,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but that is not=C2=A0always=C2=A0true, and murdering your spouse =
for the life insurance money is a fairly common plot element in <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35212621.286353/aHR0cHM6Ly9lb=
i53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRG91YmxlX0luZGVtbml0eQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
7916fcde" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">fiction</a> and also in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/35212621.286353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWlycm9yLmNvLnVrL25=
ld3MvdXMtbmV3cy9tYW4ta2lsbGVkLXdpZmUtdXNlZC1pbnN1cmFuY2UtMzI2ODg5NjA/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBd0121726" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">real life</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">On the other hand if you walked into an insurance office and asked=
 to buy a $5 million life insurance policy on your neighbor down the street=
, they would probably refuse to sell it to you. You=C2=A0have no particular=
 emotional attachment to you neighbor, as far as the insurance company know=
s, and they figure you=E2=80=99d probably be happier with him dead and $5 m=
illion than you are with him alive and no money. They don=E2=80=99t necessa=
rily think that you=E2=80=99re planning to murder him, but they=E2=80=99ll =
have suspicions. This is called the =E2=80=9Cinsurable interest=E2=80=9D re=
quirement.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are nuances. Two important ones =
are:=C2=A0</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can buy life insura=
nce on yourself, which will pay off when you die, and you can decide (befor=
e you die) who will get the payout. Often it will be your spouse or childre=
n, but you can write whoever you want into your will. (More practically, yo=
u can set up a trust while you are alive, have the insurance pay out into t=
he trust when you die, and set the beneficiaries of the trust to your heart=
=E2=80=99s content.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>) If you want to leave all your worldly possessions to Harvard Universi=
ty, then Harvard will get the $5 million when you die, and it will presumab=
ly be better off with you dead (and the money) than with you alive (and no =
money). Lots of people <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/35212621.286353/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbHVtbmkuaGFydmFyZC5lZHUvZ2l2aW5nL2JlcXVlc3=
Rz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB08339a19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">write Harvard into their will=
s</a> and Harvard does not, as far as I know, go around murdering them, tho=
ugh that would be a pretty good plot element in fiction.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you have a life insurance policy, you can=C2=A0=
<em>sell=C2=A0</em>it. There is a relatively recent history of people who t=
ake out life insurance policies, realize that their circumstances have chan=
ged, and decide that they=E2=80=99d rather get some money now than get all =
the money when they die.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0A =E2=80=9Clife settlement=E2=80=9D business exists in which inve=
stors buy these people=E2=80=99s insurance policies, make their premium pay=
ments, and collect when they die. This can be good for the people selling t=
heir policies: Instead of just letting their policies lapse for nothing, th=
e can sell the policies to get cash now. And it can be good for the investo=
rs: They get exposure to a risk (people dying) that is probably uncorrelate=
d to the rest of their investments. (It is bad for insurance companies beca=
use it means that they have to pay out on some policies that, in the absenc=
e of a resale market, would lapse.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>)=C2=A0This remains controversial, but it is a multibillion-dollar busi=
ness these days, and there do not seem to be any reported cases of the inve=
stors murdering the insureds.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact=
, the life settlement business seems to be=C2=A0so=C2=A0good that demand fo=
r insurance policies as an investment asset outstrips supply: Plenty of inv=
estors want that exposure, but there are not a lot of people, these days, w=
ith life insurance policies that they want to get rid of.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But if you combine the two nuances, a solution presents itse=
lf: People could take out new life insurance policies=C2=A0<em>specifically=
=C2=A0</em>to sell to investors.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Go to an insurance company, get a $5 million policy, have it pay =
out to a trust, make an investor the beneficiary of the trust, have the inv=
estor pay the premiums, and charge the investor a fee for the exposure. Thi=
s is called =E2=80=9Cstranger-originated life insurance,=E2=80=9D or STOLI,=
 and it is largely=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>allowed. It goes too far. It is t=
oo icky, and too far from the traditional purposes of insurance. Here is a =
2010 Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. paper on =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35212621.286353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmRpYy=
5nb3YvcmVndWxhdGlvbnMvZXhhbWluYXRpb25zL3N1cGVydmlzb3J5L2luc2lnaHRzL3Npd2luM=
TAvc2l3aW50ZXIyMDEwLWFydGljbGUwMy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb10698c1" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">Senior Life Settlements: A Cautionary Tale</a>,=E2=80=9D warning ag=
ainst it:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the case of wet-in=
k policies (new life insurance policies sold immediately after being issued=
 =E2=80=93 before the ink is dry), the applicant commits fraud on the appli=
cation by claiming he or she needs life insurance for estate planning purpo=
ses. One type of wet ink policy is STOLI.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
TOLI has many variations but only one purpose: to allow an investor without=
 an insurable interest to initiate and profit from a life insurance policy =
on a stranger. The mainstream insurance industry strongly opposes STOLI, ar=
guing it is fraud for a person to buy a policy with only a profit - and not=
 insurance - motive. STOLI is prohibited or statutorily restricted in many =
states.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it does seem to be=
 quite a business, with agents and brokers going around looking for older c=
ustomers to take out insurance policies to resell to investors.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a> They seem to be on shaky legal ground in many places.=C2=A0But if you =
are an investor who buys life insurance policies on the secondary market, y=
ou don=E2=80=99t necessarily=C2=A0<em>know </em>the history of the insuranc=
e policy. Perhaps the insured bought the policy for her legitimate estate-p=
lanning purposes, changed her mind, and sold it for cash. Or perhaps a brok=
er talked her into buying the policy specifically to resell it. If it=E2=80=
=99s the former, then you can go ahead and buy it and collect the death ben=
efit. If it=E2=80=99s the latter, then you can=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/35212621.286353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMjkvYXBvbGxvLWFjY3VzZWQtaW4tbGF3c3VpdC1vZi1pbGxlZ2FsLWh1bWFu=
LWxpZmUtd2FnZXJpbmctc2NoZW1lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MzAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0a76495" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here=E2=80=
=99s this</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apollo Global Ma=
nagement Inc. bet on the longevity of senior citizens by acquiring illegal =
life insurance policies and funneling the payouts through shell entities, a=
ccording to a new lawsuit. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CApo=
llo has been carrying out a widespread fraudulent human life wagering consp=
iracy designed to not only hide its involvement, but to create the false ap=
pearance that the policies it owns are somehow legitimate,=E2=80=9D accordi=
ng to the complaint. =E2=80=9CWorse still, when Apollo senses a claim is go=
ing to be brought, it attempts to dissolve its shell entities to give itsel=
f yet another layer of protection.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>A spokesperson for Apollo didn=E2=80=99t immediately respond to a request =
for comment Monday.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawsuit was filed A=
pril 26 in Delaware=E2=80=99s Chancery Court by the estate of Martha Barotz=
, whose policy allegedly paid out $5 million after she died in 2018. The ca=
se stems from earlier litigation between the Barotz estate and the Apollo-l=
inked trusts, along with the estate=E2=80=99s subsequent attempts to collec=
t on the nearly $7 million judgment it won, according to the new complaint.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The policy allegedly originated in 2006 wh=
en Barotz, then in her 70s, agreed to let an enterprise called Life Accumul=
ation Trust III take out the policy in exchange for a payment equaling 3% o=
f the death benefit. Stranger-originated policies are often securitized in =
large portfolios that obscure their details from the people they =E2=80=9Cp=
rey on,=E2=80=9D according to the lawsuit.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9CIn this way, the senior citizens have no idea who owns a policy on=
 their life, and who wants them dead,=E2=80=9D the suit says. =E2=80=9CThis=
 is precisely what happened with the policy here.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Martha Barotz died in 2018, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35212621.286353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGVn=
YWN5LmNvbS91cy9vYml0dWFyaWVzL255dGltZXMvbmFtZS9tYXJ0aGEtYmFyb3R6LW9iaXR1YXJ=
