>investors argued</a> that actually=C2=A0<em>Barotz=C2=A0</em>had done a fr=
aud on=C2=A0<em>them:=C2=A0</em>She took the $150,000 to set up the policy =
for investors, and then her estate tried to get the money back: =E2=80=9CDe=
fendants raise arguments that Ms. Barotz was, purportedly, the sole driving=
 force in the =E2=80=98fraudulent scheme=E2=80=99 to benefit herself and he=
r family, and that her estate should not be able to benefit from Ms. Barotz=
's =E2=80=98unclean hands.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D It does seem a little odd that=
 they paid her for the policy, they paid the premiums, and her estate gets =
to keep the money. But the court was not sympathetic to the investors=E2=80=
